results.notes: One for the life list! I had always heard about the “desert stalked puffball,” and what do you know, they were growing right there along the road near a British World War I cemetery in Southern Italy. Wasn’t even looking in particular or aware that they might be around. Almost missed them, to be honest, because of how well hidden they were in the sandy soil and leaf litter. Mixed trees around, some oak. Sandy soil. Low moisture. Thought it was something like a Boletellus betula because of the long reticulated stem. Then the white volva fell off the top to reveal an orange spore sac. Definitely something else, puffball-esque. The lower volva extended substantially into the dirt below. Did not smell, cross-section, taste, collect.

results.notes: Found these growing in a mulch pile where I sometimes find Lepista nuda and amanitas. At first thought they had a chance of being a variety of oyster mushroom because of the tight features of the young buttons and the offset (notched) caps. But it wasn’t a good fit, and my partner and I felt up for ID’ing some LBMs. The caps were pleasantly smooth but not truly viscid when wet. The mushrooms were substantial for their size and almost rubbery in the hand. Especially the more mature specimens had a distinctive bump on the cap (umbonate) and a lobed appearance. The stipe did not bruise and had a stringy texture. Inrolled margin on young specimens. No veil. White spore print. Notched gills. Did have a radish-like flavor. Eaten pretty gleefully upon determination that they were likely the “fried chicken mushroom” or a close relative.

results.notes:
Growing abundantly and gregariously on dead, fallen Phytolacca americana stems. Apothecia superficial and lacking an obvious subiculum. Discs drying dull orange-brown within several days. Ascocarps turned black when viewed in July of 2021. All structures inamyloid. No distinctive reaction in 1M KOH. Fringed with straight, brown, multi-septate hairs irregularly encrusted elong their lengths. Hair apices hyaline. Ectal excipulum of textura angularis made up of brown cells. Paraphyses lanceolate and encrusted in 1M KOH, encrusted material dissolving in Melzer’s reagent. Paraphyses measurements: (50.1) 55.9 – 74.8 (78.8) × (3.7) 4.1 – 5.4 (5.9) µm, Q = (10.6) 11.2 – 16.7 (18.5); N = 30, Me = 65.1 × 4.8 µm; Qe = 13.8. Paraphyses exceeding asci by 5.6 – 21.8 µm (40 measured). Asci unitunicate, inoperculate, 8-spored and lacking croziers. Asci measurements: (53.7) 57.2 – 78.2 (79.9) × (6.4) 6.5 – 7.8 (8.3) µm, Q = (6.7) 7.3 – 11; N = 30, Me = 68.9 × 7.2 µm; Qe = 9.6. Spores smooth, hyaline, thin-walled, lacking guttules and 0-septate. Spore measurements: (9.4) 10.5 – 12.4 (13.2) × (2.3) 2.4 – 3.2 (3.6) µm, Q = (3) 3.4 – 4.9 (5.5); N = 30, Me = 11.2 × 2.8 µm; Qe = 4.1
